                          ]
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "frame",
                      "id": "GYwO1",
                      "name": "Explanation markdown body",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "layout": "vertical",
                      "gap": 12,
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "Z4ArKl",
                          "fill": "$--foreground",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "Most people sign in to apps these days with one click: they tap \"Continue with Google\" and they're in. Asking them to invent yet another password is the friction step that loses sign-ups. Adding Google sign-in is the single highest-impact thing we can do to lift conversion on this screen.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.65,
                          "fontFamily": "$--font-serif",
                          "fontSize": 15,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "W3345b",
                          "fill": "$--foreground",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "How it works under the hood: when the user clicks the button, we redirect them to Google's sign-in page (we never see their password — Google handles that). Once they approve, Google sends them back to us with a signed token called a JWT. A JWT is a signed token Google gives the browser after sign-in, like a stamped admission ticket — the browser hands it to our server and our server can trust who the user is without re-checking the password.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.65,
                          "fontFamily": "$--font-serif",
                          "fontSize": 15,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "S6JnQ",
                          "fill": "$--foreground",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "The interesting wrinkle: a user might already have an account here under the same email (from email+password). When their Google sign-in arrives, we don't want to create a duplicate account — we want to recognize them and link the two methods. That's what \"auto-link on trusted provider\" does: because Google has already verified the email upstream, we treat the Google sign-in as proof that the same person owns the existing email/password account.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.65,
                          "fontFamily": "$--font-serif",
                          "fontSize": 15,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "RsNSX",
                          "fill": "$--foreground",
                          "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                          "width": "fill_container",
                          "content": "What we are NOT doing in this Subtask: account-recovery flows, social providers beyond Google, or a profile-settings UI to manage connected accounts. Those land later — this Subtask is just the sign-in flow.",
                          "lineHeight": 1.65,
                          "fontFamily": "$--font-serif",
                          "fontSize": 15,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
